# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chechen-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Abaza is spoken by approximately 35,000 people in Russia, where it is written in a Cyrillic alphabet, as well as another 10,000 in Turkey, where the Latin script is used.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] It consists of two dialects, the Ashkherewa dialect and the T'ap'anta dialect, which is the literary standard.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The language also consists of five subdialects known as Psyzh-Krasnovostok, Abazakt, Apsua, Kubin-Elburgan and Kuvin.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Abaza, like its relatives in the family of Northwest Caucasian languages, is a highly agglutinative language.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] For example, the verb in the English sentence "He couldn't make them give it back to her" contains four arguments (a term used in valency grammar): *he*, *them*, *it*, *to her*.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Abaza marks arguments morphologically, and incorporates all four arguments as pronominal prefixes on the verb.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] It has a large consonantal inventory (63 phonemes) coupled with a minimal vowel inventory (two vowels).
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] It is very closely related to Abkhaz, but it preserves a few phonemes which Abkhaz lacks, such as a voiced pharyngeal fricative.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Work on Abaza has been carried out by W.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Allen, Brian O'Herin, and John Colarusso.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Different forms of cultural assimilation contributed to its fall in use in areas of Russia, and over time its overall endangerment.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The language can be broken into five different dialects and has several unique grammatical approaches to languages.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language was at its peak usage in the mid to late 19th century.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Abaza speakers along the Greater and Lesser Laba, Urup, and Greater and Lesser Zelenchuk rivers are from a wave of migrants in the 17th to 18th centuries who represent the Abaza speakers of today.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The end of the Great Caucasian War in 1864 provided Russia with power and control of the local regions and contributed to the decrease in the popularity of pre-existing local languages prior to the war.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language was not a written language until the Latin alphabet was adopted in 1932–1933 to write it.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The Cyrillic script was later utilized to write the language in 1938.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] A small amount of books, pamphlets, and a newspaper were published in the Abaza language afterwards.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language is spoken in Russia and Turkey.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Although it is endangered, it is still spoken in several regions in Russia.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] These include Kara-Pago, Kubina, Psyzh, El'burgan, Inzhich-Chukun, Koi-dan, Abaza-Khabl', Malo-Abazinka, Tapanta, Krasnovostochni, Novokuvinski, Starokuvinski, Abazakt and Ap-sua.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The vowels [o, a, u] may have a /j/ in front of it.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The vowels [e] and [i] are allophones of /a/ and /ə/ (respectively) before palatalized consonants, while the vowels [o] and [u] are allophones of /a/ and /ə/ (respectively) before labialized consonants.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The vowels [e], [o], [i], and [u] can also occur as variants of the sequences /aj/, /aw/, /əj/ and /əw/.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Abaza does not have the long low vowel found in Kabardian, preserving it as /aʕ/ or /ʕa/.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, there were attempts to write Abaza with the Arabic script, but none of these attempts took hold.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] In 1932, the first widely used Abaza alphabet was created using the Latin script.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Since 1938, Abaza has been written with the version of the Cyrillic alphabet shown below.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] The digraphs Лӏ and Фӏ are dialectal, and are therefore absent from the literary language and the official alphabet.
[src:chechen-language/abaza-language] Sultan Laguchev, a singer-songwriter famous in Russia, writes and performs songs in the Abaza language, including "Абыгъь гӏважьква" and "БаъапI бара." He has written an additional song in Russian entitled "Мы абазины" ('We are Abazins') about Abazinia.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz is a Northwest Caucasian language and is thus related to Adyghe.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The language of Abkhaz is especially close to Abaza, and they are sometimes considered dialects of the same language, Abazgi, of which the literary dialects of Abkhaz and Abaza are simply two ends of a dialect continuum.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Grammatically, the two are very similar; however, the differences in phonology are substantial, it also contains elements characteristic of Kabardian; these are the main reasons for many others to prefer keeping the two separate, while others still refer to it as the Tapanta dialect of Abkhaz.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Chirikba mentions that there are possible indications that proto-Northwest Caucasian, could have divided firstly into proto-Circassian and to proto-Ubykh-Abkhaz; Ubykh then being the closest relative to Abkhaz, with it only later on being influenced by Circassian.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There is not an agreed number of speakers of Abkhaz, and there are widely different numbers.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] It is agreed that today most of the Abkhaz people do not live in Abkhazia.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In the census conducted by the Republic of Abkhazia in 2011, Abkhazians comprised 50.8% of the population, around 122,175 people; of these 92,838 spoke it natively.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Only two of the original dialects are still spoken in Abkhazia.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The Bzyp dialect is still spoken in its homeland northwest of Sukhumi, stretching from the Bzyp River to the western environs of Sukhumi and the Psyrtskha valley, whereas the Abzhywa dialect is spoken south-east of Sukhumi.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The rest of the Abkhaz speaking population inhabits other neighbouring areas.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The exact number of Abkhazians and Abkhaz speakers in Turkey is not clear.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The Turkish census denotes 13,951, but the figures are dubious, since the numbers of Abkhazians that came from the beginning of the 19th century to the middle of the 20th have been documented at around 30 thousand.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] *Ethnologue* gives 150,000 Abkhazians living in Turkey, of these 50,000 still speak the language.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The head of the Abkhaz federation says there are in between 500 and 700 thousand Abkhazians in Turkey.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Historically the dialects of Sadz, Ahchypsy and Tsabal were located in Abkhazia; Sadz being spoken from the Bzyp river to the Matsesta River, and further to the north-west bordering the Sochypsta River.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Today they are exclusively spoken in the northwestern part of Turkey, specially in the Sakarya province, it being spoken in 14 villages.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The other major place where Abkhaz is spoken is in Karachay-Cherkessia, where the Northern dialects are spoken, although there they are considered as a separate language and form the literary Abaza language.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] They are spoken by 37,831 people in Russia, mostly in the south of Stavropol Krai in the area around Kislovodsk, and in the upper Kuma river area.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz is also spoken as a minority language around the world.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There is a considerable number of Abkhaz speakers in Adjara in southern Georgia, with the diaspora concentrating itself around the capital Batumi, with about 982 people considering Abkhaz their first language.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In the Russian census of 2010, 6,786 speakers of Abkhaz were reported in Russia.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In Ukraine there are around 1,458 according to the 2001 census, but of these only 317 speak Abkhazian.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There were also communities in Syria, Jordan and Iraq with around 5,000 Abkhazians, although this number could reach 10,000 according to the Abkhazia's Foreign Ministry.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The biggest western diaspora is in Germany, with around 5,000 speakers, but other communities are found in countries such as the United States, United Kingdom, Austria, France, Belgium and so on.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The earliest indisputable extant written records of the Abkhaz language are in the Arabic script, recorded by the Turkish traveller Evliya Çelebi in the 17th century.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has been used as a literary language for only about 100 years.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] It was suggested that certain inscriptions on Ancient Greek pottery which had been considered nonsense are in fact written in Abkhaz-Adydge languages.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The methodology of the research was criticised and the results called improbable.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In 1918, Tbilisi State University became the first institution of higher education to teach Abkhazian language.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The founders of the university began to take care of the development and scientific study of the Abkhazian language.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] At the meeting of the Council of Professors held at Tbilisi State University in 1918, Ivane Javakhishvili noted the scientific importance of studying Caucasian languages.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In 1918, by the decision of the Council of Professors, Petre Charaia was invited to teach the Abkhazian language, and from 1925, this mission was continued by Dimitri Gulia and Simon Janashia.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Both Georgian and Abkhaz law enshrines an official status of the Abkhaz language in Abkhazia.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The 1992 law of Georgia, reiterated in the 1995 constitution, grants Abkhaz the status of second official language in the territory of Abkhazia — along with Georgian.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In November 2007, the de facto authorities of Abkhazia adopted a new law "on the state language of the Republic of Abkhazia" that mandates Abkhaz as the language of official communication.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The law is an attempt to amend a situation where up to a third of the ethnic Abkhaz population are no longer capable of speaking their ethnic language, and even more are unable to read or write it; instead, Russian is the language most commonly used in public life at present.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The literary language is based on the Abzhywa dialect.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In some form or the other, all dialects are richer in phonemes than the standard Abzhywa dialect.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The only dialects spoken in Abkhazia are Abzhywa and Bzyp.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Northern dialects which are the basis for literary Abaza are spoken in Karachay-Cherkessia, while the other dialects such as Sadz are spoken in Turkey due to Russian invasions in the 19th century.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] While most differences are phonetic, differences in the lexicon are present, although mostly due to exterior contact.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Bzyp contains the most preserved lexicon, with few borrowings.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abzhywa has adopted many loans from Kartvelian, specially Mingrelian; Sadz on the other hand has more words from Circassian.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Northern dialects in general have more loanwords from Persian, Arabic, Turkish and Circassian.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has a very large number of consonants (58 in the literary dialect), with three-way voiced/voiceless/ejective and palatalized/labialized/plain distinctions.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] By contrast, the language has only two phonemically distinct vowels, which have several allophones depending on the palatal and/or labial quality of adjacent consonants.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Labialised alveolo-palatal fricatives are found in the Bzyp and Sadz dialects of Abkhaz, but not in Abzhywa.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Plain alveolo-palatal consonants and the pharyngealised and labialised-pharyngealised uvular fricatives are unique to the Bzyp dialect.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The consonants highlighted in red and in brackets are the 4 kinds of labialisation described by Chirikba.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Found in the Bzyp and Sadz dialects of Abkhaz, but not in Abzhywa.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The nature of the vowels of Abkhaz is not clear.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Some linguists, characterise the vowel system as a 2 degree vertical vowel system; with the two vowels being distinguished by height, 'ә' being the high/close vowel, and 'а' being the low/open.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] This system would very closely resemble the one found in Adyghe.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The quality of 'ә' in this case, is usually represented as [ɨ] if the vowel is in a stressed position, and being unaffected by its neighbouring consonants.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Other linguists however, mainly Russian ones, describe the vowels differently.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] They describe the sound of 'ә' being completely different from [ɨ], and by their descriptions being closer to [ə].
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The 'а' is described as being particularly back, likely [ɑ].
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has used the Cyrillic script since 1862.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The first alphabet was a 37-character Cyrillic alphabet invented by Baron Peter von Uslar.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In 1909 a 55-letter Cyrillic alphabet was used.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] A 75-letter Latin script devised by a Russian/Georgian linguist Nikolai Marr lasted for 2 years 1926–1928 (during the Latinization campaign).
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The Georgian script was adopted and used between 1938 and 1954, after that the initial Cyrillic alphabet, designed in 1892 by Dmitry Gulia together with Konstantin Machavariani and modified in 1909 by Aleksey Chochua, was restored to use.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The Latin alphabet in Abkhaz is currently not in Unicode.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Typical of Northwest Caucasian languages, Abkhaz is an agglutinative language that relies heavily on affixation.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] It has an ergative-absolutive typology, such that the subject of an intransitive verb functions identically to the object of a transitive verb.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Notably, Abkhaz expresses ergativity entirely through the ordering of subjects and objects within verb constructions rather than through overt case marking as most other ergative languages do.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] All Latin transliterations in this section utilize the system explicated in Chirikba (2003) (see Abkhaz alphabet for the details).
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz, being an ergative language, makes a strong distinction between transitive and intransitive verbs, as well as dynamic and stative.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs describe states of being, roughly analogous to copular phrases in English, as in дхәыҷуп (*d-x˚əčә́-wə-p* - "she is a child").
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs express direct actions, functioning more closely to standard English verbs.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs possess the full range of aspect, mood and tense forms, in contrast to statives, which do not.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Some verbs, called inversives, combine certain features of both stative and dynamic verbs.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Another important verbal distinction in Abkhaz is finite versus non-finite.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Finite verbs usually contain enough information to form a complete sentence, whereas non-finite verbs typically form dependent clauses.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Verb stems can be derived in a number of ways, including compounding, affixation, reduplication or conversion from another part of speech.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Roughly equivalent to the infinitive, or to a so-called "verbal noun," the **Masdar** form of the verb resembles the English gerund.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] It is formed by the addition of a specific suffix to a bare verb stem, -ра (*-ra*) for a dynamic verb and -заара (*-zaara*) for a stative.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] However, the fully conjugated personal Abkhaz verb forms are "templatic," with each grammatical distinction occupying a specific "slot" or "position" within the broader verb template.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Verbs are thus formed by the addition of various affixes to the verb stem; these affixes express such distinctions as transitivity, person and stative/dynamic quality, occupying rigid positions within the overall verb structure.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There is a high degree of agreement between verbs and other parts of speech.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Not all of these elements will necessarily co-occur in every verb.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The individual parts of verb morphology are addressed below.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The first prefixing element of the verb complex expresses either the subject of an intransitive verb in the absolutive construction, or the direct object of a transitive verb in an ergative construction.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The following table illustrates the various agreement markers which can occupy the first position.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] These prefixes can either be in their long forms, containing the letters inside the parenthesis, or in the short forms that do not contain them.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] If the stress falls on the prefix, the long form is used.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] If the prefix is not followed by a consonant cluster, the short form is used.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] If the stress does not fall on the prefix, the short form is used.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] It is also possible for the possessive prefix ҽы́- (*čə́-*) in a reflexive construction or the relative prefix иы́- (*jә́-*) in a non-finite construction to occupy this position.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The second position is occupied by the indirect object or by the prefix аи- (*aj-*) for reciprocal pronouns equivalent to "each other" or "one another" in English.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] This position accommodates a number of prefixes.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Any indirect object occurring after the one in the second position occupies this position instead; a possessive prefix of stative verbs can also be placed here.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Where a possessive prefix exists in the first position, the reflexive prefix is placed here.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] This position is occupied by preverbal elements which are not an explicit part of the verb stem.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Preverbal elements that are explicitly attached to the verb stem take this position.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The agreement marker corresponding to the agent (the subject of a transitive verb) takes this position.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The negation prefix m- occupies this position in a dynamic verb construction.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The causative prefix r- takes the final position before the verb stem.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The first of the suffixing elements expresses adverbial information relating to "inside" (-la) or "outside" (-aa).
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Several aspect markers occupy this position as suffixes.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Several tense markers occupy this position, dependent upon whether the verb in question is stative or dynamic.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs have a richly developed tense paradigm incorporating tense and aspect distinctions.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The table below illustrates these various dynamic tense forms using the verb агара (*agara* – "to take").
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs, by contrast, lack this rich tense system, as illustrated below using the verb а́цәара (*ácºara* - "to be sleeping").
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The negation prefix m- occupies this position in a stative verb construction.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The final position in the verb complex can accommodate any one of several mixed purpose markers.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The **imperative** takes a few possible forms, depending upon the type of verb.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs form the imperative by the addition of agreement suffixes to a bare verb stem; intransitives include the subject and indirect object makers, whereas transitives include the direct object and absolutive.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs form the imperative simply by adding the durative suffix -z to the verb stem.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz lacks diathetic opposition, and as such there is no true passive voice distinction.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Like verbs, Abkhaz nouns are formed by the addition of various prefixes and suffixes to a static noun stem.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Noun stems can be derived according to several different processes, including compounding, reduplication, or the addition of a derivational affix.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The affixes mark number, definiteness and possession, as well as some case-like elements.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] As with verbs, not all of these elements can occur at the same time.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The individual parts of noun morphology are addressed below.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There is a range of definiteness in Abkhaz.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Those articles adhering to definite/generic categories appear as prefixes in the broader noun structure, whereas the indefinite is suffixed.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The absence of either article affix implies a zero reference implying universal quantifiers, or to express the total lack of a referent.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Definite and indefinite affixes may appear together in the same noun, implying that the referents are meant as a group or body.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There are some semantic differences in article usage between the different dialects of Abkhaz.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] These are possessive prefixes which express grammatical person and noun class.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] They come in two forms, the full and short ones.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The full ones contain the vowels inside the parenthesis, whereas the short ones do not.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] These few prefixes add numeric information to the noun complex.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Often, this takes the form of a numeral.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Inflectional suffixes can follow each other sequentially.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz distinguishes singular and plural; the singular is unmarked, whereas the plural is indicated by noun class-dependent suffixes.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There are several pluralizing suffixes, but the two most commonly used refer generally to the human and non-human noun classes.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There are instances where explicitly human nouns take non-human plural markers.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] There are also several plural endings that are of much narrower use.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The clitic -гьы (*-g’ə*) functions as an in-built coordinating conjunction.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Nouns in Abkhaz are classified broadly according to a human/non-human paradigm, with the human class itself further subdivided into masculine and feminine gender.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Gender is a fairly weak concept in Abkhaz grammar, and gender distinctions undergo a fair degree of neutralization in several contexts, including personal pronouns, verb agreement and possession marking.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] This class and gender system distinguishes Abkhaz from the other Northwest Caucasian languages.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Although there is no special vocative declension, the prefix уа- (*wa-*), when attached to a noun stem, can express a vocative form.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Similarly, the suffix -a can be added to a proper noun ending in a consonant to communicate respect and endearment.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Pronouns are not inflected, and verbal agreement is generally sufficient to indicate grammatical person.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] It is common in everyday speech to use a short version of the pronoun which omits the suffix -рá (*-rá*), although this is done less frequently with third-person pronouns.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] In addition to noun-marking, **possession** can be indicated by adding the suffix -тәы́ (*-t’˚ә́*) to the short version of a personal pronoun.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Morphologically, adjectives are very similar to nouns, differing only in their syntactic function.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Similarly to nouns, adjective stems can be derived by compounding, reduplication and affixation.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] When used attributively, adjectives follow the noun that they modify.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Predicative adjectives, or those derived by suffixation, precede the noun.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The possessive prefix r- is used to show possessive agreement.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] These suffixes are added to the adjective stem to show agreement with the noun being modified.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The comparative form of an adjective is formed using the comparative particle аиҳá (*ajhá* - "more"), which precedes the adjective.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] The superlative form is indicated by the intensifier suffix -ӡа.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] Дарбанзаалак ауаҩы дшоуп ихы дақәиҭны. Ауаа зегь зинлеи патулеи еиҟароуп. Урҭ ирымоуп ахшыҩи аламыси, дара дарагь аешьеи аешьеи реиԥш еизыҟазароуп.
[src:chechen-language/abkhaz-language] "All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] In grammar, the **absolutive case** (abbreviated **abs**) is the case of nouns in ergative–absolutive languages that would generally be the subjects of intransitive verbs or the objects of transitive verbs in the translational equivalents of nominative–accusative languages such as English.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] In languages with ergative–absolutive alignment, the absolutive is the case used to mark both the subject of an intransitive verb and the object of a transitive verb in addition to being used for the citation form of a noun.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] It contrasts with the marked ergative case, which marks the subject of a transitive verb.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] In a very few cases, a marked absolutive has been reported, including in Nias and Sochiapam Chinantec.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] Occasionally, the term 'absolutive case' (or also: 'absolute case') is used for the unmarked case form in languages with other alignment types.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] This is especially common in the tradition of descriptive linguistics of African languages.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] In marked nominative languages, where the nominative has case inflection, the accusative is unmarked and also serves as citation form.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] In these languages, the unmarked accusative/citation form is thus often called 'absolutive'.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] On the other hand, in certain nominative–accusative languages, it is the accusative which is explicitly marked for case, whereas the nominative is unmarked and serves as citation form.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] In such situations, the term 'absolutive' is occasionally used to describe the unmarked nominative/citation form.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] In tripartite languages, both the agent and object of a transitive clause have case forms, ergative and accusative, and the agent of an intransitive clause is the unmarked citation form.
[src:chechen-language/absolutive-case] It is occasionally called the intransitive case, but *absolutive* is also used and is perhaps more accurate since it is not limited to core agents of intransitive verbs.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] The **Abzakh dialect** (Adyghe: Абдзахабзэ; Kabardian: Абдзахэбзэ) is one of the Adyghe language dialects.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] The Abzakh dialect is spoken by the Abzakh which are one of the largest Circassian population in the diaspora outside Republic of Adygea alongside Shapsugs.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Historically, Proto-Circassian possessed a distinct series of stops and affricates.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Phase 1 (Spirantization): The original affricates weakened into fricatives or glottal stops.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Phase 2 (Velar Palatalization): Historical palatalized velars shifted forward to fill the "gap" left by the changes in Phase 1.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] The following sections detail how these shifts occurred and provide comparative examples.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] The first major shift occurred in the Abzakh and Kabardian dialects, where the original affricate postalveolar consonants and affricate retroflex consonants underwent spirantization, becoming fricatives.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] One exception was that the original postalveolar ejective affricate [tʃʼ] ⟨чӏ⟩ did not just become a fricative; in Abzakh, it often debuccalized to a palatalized glottal stop ʔʲ ⟨ӏь⟩ (or simply ⟨ӏ⟩).
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] The following table details the timeline of this evolution specifically within Abzakh, showing how words shifted from Proto-Circassian, to an intermediate Proto-Abzakh stage, and finally to Modern Abzakh.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Later on, after the original affricates had become fricatives or glottal stops, a gap was left in the postalveolar position.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] In the majority of Circassian dialects (including standard Adyghe and Kabardian), the historical velar consonants shifted forward to fill this gap.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] The velars ⟨гь⟩ [ɡʲ], ⟨кь⟩ [kʲ] and ⟨кӏь⟩ [kʲʼ] became the new palato-alveolar consonants ⟨дж⟩ [d͡ʒ], ⟨ч⟩ [t͡ʃ] and ⟨кӏ⟩ [t͡ʃʼ] respectively.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] The following table demonstrates how these words are distinct in archaic dialects (like Shapsug) but have merged or shifted in Standard Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] The Voiceless velar fricative [x] becomes the aspirated Voiceless velar plosive [kʰ] (like English *c* in *car*, *cup*, *cop*, or *curse*) after the Voiceless postalveolar fricative [ʃ].
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] In this environment, the velar fricative undergoes hardening to become a plosive.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] This change only occurred in some Abzakh sub-dialects and in Bzhedug dialects.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] This should not be confused with the palatalized kʲ (like English *c* in *camera*, *cannon*, or *cow*).
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Khakurinokhabl sub-dialect of Abzakh, the instrumental case has the suffix -мӏе (-mʔʲa) or -ӏе (-ʔʲa) unlike other dialects that has the suffix -мкӏэ (-mt͡ʃa) or -кӏэ (-t͡ʃa).
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Standard Adyghe, The prefix зэкӏэ- means backward.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Standard Adyghe, The prefix чӏэ- means under (toward under).
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо ахэмытэу нартхэр былымыхьэ кӏогъагъэх. Былымхэр къагъоти, къежьэжьыхи Къойданэм къэсыгъэх. Саусырыкъо дэмысыгъэу щытыти, къыхэкӏижьи, янэ дэжь къихьажьыгъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сыгъашх, тян, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо. — Сыгъашх, сыгъашх оӏо зэпыты, ущыс, модыкӏэ нартыхэр былым къахьи, Къойданым къэсыжьыгъэх, — къыриӏуагъ янэ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Нартымэ сырямыгъусагъэми, ащ къахьырэмэ анахьышӏуӏомкӏэ садэгощэн, тян, — ыӏуагъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Пӏэстэ шыӏэ щтыгъ, лы жъогъэ щтыгъ, щыбжьый-шыгъу атетэкъуагъэу ӏанэм къытыригъэуцуагъэх янэ. Саусырыкъо пӏастэр ыфызи, псыр къыӏифыгъ, лыр ыутхыпкӏи мылыхэр къыпигъэтэкъуи ышхыгъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ныбжьи нахь дэгъоу сыбгъэшхагъэп, тян, — ыӏуи къикӏижьыгъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо Тхъожъыем къытетӏысхьи, Къойданым кӏонэу ежьагъ. Саусырыкъо къакӏоу нартхэм залъэгъум, шӏэныгъэ иӏэу зы лӏы горэ ахэтыти: «Саусырыкъо мыгъо цӏыкӏур къэкӏозы, «фэсыжь апщи, нартхэ», зиӏокӏэ «тхьэуегъэпсэу» — шъуӏо нахь, «ахад» — шъумыӏо», — къариӏуагъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Зэриӏуагъэм фэдэу, тыдэкӏэ ахэхьагъэми «тхьэуегъэпсэу» къыраӏуагъ нахь, «ахад» къыраӏуагъзп.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Етӏанэ, Саусырыкъо губжъи, ежь зыфиӏорэр къыдэхъоу щытыти, щэщищ гъурӏи зишӏи шыӏэм зэтыригъэлӏагъэх.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Мэшӏо тӏэкӏу тэзгъэгъотырэр ӏэхьэгъу тшӏыщт зы ӏахьэкӏэ. — аӏуагъ нартымэ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сз шъозгъэгъотыщт, — ариӏуи, тау-таш горэм ӏугъо тӏэкӏу къыдихэу ылъэгъугъэти, Саусырыкъо ащ кӏуагъэ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Лэгъупышхом лы илъэу, пхъэцэӏитӏу, зы инырэ, зы цӏыкӏурэ пэлъэу, иныжъыри ащ къещэкӏигъэу пэӏулъэу къыӏухьагъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Машӏом икъыпэхыкӏэу хъущтыр Саусырыкъо ымышӏэу егупшысэу щытызэ, Тхъожъыер къэгущыӏи: «Уишыӏядзэ къыӏехи, упкӏэ цуакъэ сфэшӏ. Бажьэм фэдэу зызгъэзэщт, цызэм фэдэу сыкъэкӏощт, лъэгонжэмышъхьэкӏэ зесыдзыхынызы, пхъэцакӏэ иным уемыӏэу, цӏыкӏур къашти, тхьыны тыкӏожьыщт, — къыриӏуагъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Ишыӏядзэ къыӏихи, упкӏэ цуакъэ фишӏыгь. Къекӏуалӏи, Тхъожъыем лъэгонжэмышхьэкӏэ зыридзыхыгъ. Саусырыкъо пхъэцэкӏэ цӏыкӏум еӏэ шӏошӏызэ, иным еӏи, иныжъым тыригъафи, къыгъэущыгъ. Къэӏаби, Саусырыкъо рилъэшъохи шыр шъхьартӏупщэу хъугъэ, Саусырыкъуи иныжъым ипӏэшъхьагъ ӏилъхьагъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сыд уилъэгъунэу укъызыфэкӏуагъэр? — ыӏуи иныжъыр къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Шыӏэ тылӏэти мэшӏо тӏзкӏу схьынэу сыкъэкӏуагъ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Саусырыкъо ихьэгьо-шӏагъохэмэ ашышэу зы къаумэ къысаӏуи, устӏупщыжьыщт, — ыӏуагъ иныжъым.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Саусырыкъо ихьэгъо-шӏагъомэ ащышэу сэ зэхэсхыгъзу зы къаумэ къыосӏон, ау сэ ежь слъэгъугьахэп, — ыӏуагъ. — Саусырыкъо жьан щэрэхъыр къушъхьэм дарегъэхьые, къырарегъэфыхи, копкъышъхьэкӏэ еозы дефыежьы.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо дихьыен ылъэкӏыщтэпти, ежь иныжъым жьан щэрэхъыр къушъхьэм дихьий, Саусырыкъо къырыригьэшэхыгъ. Иныр копкъышъхьэӏе къеуи, къыдифыежьыгъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ащ пэмыӏеу пшӏзрэ щыӏэмэ, къаӏо, — ыӏуагъ иным.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Цобзэ-шӏобзыр плъыжьыбзэу егъэплъызы, ыжэ кӏоцӏ делъхьазы егъэкӏуасэ аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ, — риӏуагь.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Иныжъым цобзэ-шӏобзыр плъыжьыбзэу ыгъэплъи, ыжэ дилъхьи, ыгъэкӏосагъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сӏукӏоцӏ хъутэ-плъытэщти, ыгъэусэни, сигъэтхъэжьыгъ. Ай нэмыӏеу сы пшӏэрэ? — ыӏуи къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ай нэмыӏеу, псыр егъажъо, псы жъуагъэм хэгьуалъхьэзы зегъэпскӏы.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Иныжъым гъоплъэ хьэкъуашъокӏэ псыр къыгъажъуи, машӏор ӏешӏыхьагъэу хэгъуалъхьи зигъэпскӏыгъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Шъохъу-тӏэхъум сигъалӏэщтыгъ, сыдэу ӏэзэгъу шӏагъо къысэпӏуагъ, сиӏял, — къыриӏуагъ. — Джыри сыд ышӏэу зэхэпхыгъэр?
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ай нэмыӏеу, ыхыкъын къэсэу псым зыхигьэщтыхьати, щэщ-мэфищэ хэтыщтыгъэ, етӏанэ къыкъутэти къыхэкӏижьыщтыгъ, — аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Адэ ар таущытэу ыгъэщтытыгъэ, сыд ышӏэщтыгъэр? — ыӏуи иныжъыр къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сшӏэрэп, зыгорэ еӏошъы псыр егъэщты аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Псым хэуцу, — ыӏуи ытыкъыны къэсэу псым хигъэуцуагъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Ежь Саусырыкъо ышӏэу щытыти, щэщищым къэхъущт щтырыгъуӏир къышӏи, иныжъыр хигъэщтыхьагъ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Къеӏ, — ыӏуи къызеӏэм, мылыр къыгъэцӏацӏэу, къыгъачэу хъугъэ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] — Зэ зыгъэбыяу, щыгъупшагъэ сшӏыгъэ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо. — Саусырыкъо мылыр къыхичыти, псы къытыригъэлъадэщтыгъ, хьауарзэ хитакъоти, ыгъзщтыжьыти, къытыригъэсэжьыщтыгъэ.
[src:chechen-language/abzakh-dialect] Ащ фэдэу ышӏи: — Къеӏ, нныжъ, —зыреӏом, къьыкӏаӏи шъхьзкӏэ мылыр къыфэгъэхъыягъэп.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde was originally brought to Cameroon in the early parts of the 19th century during a religious war (Jihad) that was launched by Usman dan Fodio from Northern Nigeria.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] It is an Atlantic language that belongs to the Niger–Congo language family.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The speakers of the language are the Fulani people.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The language itself is divided into a number of sub-dialects: Maroua, Garoua, Ngaondéré, Kambariire, Mbororoore, and Bilkire.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Sudan, the language is spoken mainly in Blue Nile, Gedaref, and Sennar states with some communities of speakers also found in North Kordofan and South Kordofan states.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In South Sudan, it is spoken in Western Bahr el Ghazal state by Ambororo cattle herders.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Chad, it is spoken in Lac Léré Department in the Mayo-Kebbi Ouest Region.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Nigeria, it is spoken in Adamawa and Taraba states.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] While in Cameroon the language is widespread across the Far North and Northern regions of the country.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The word order for Adamawa Fulfulde is SOV (subject–object–verb).
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde is mostly written in a modified Arabic script, in the tradition of Ajami script, that it shares with many other languages such as Hausa language, and many other languages in Sub-Sahara Africa.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Writing Fulfulde with Arabic script has a long tradition and old manuscripts are found in all of West Africa.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Latin alphabet is also used for writing of Adamawa.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The usage of Latin is a lot more recent, only coming to existence with the arrival of European Christian.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Still, in Cameroon, Arabic alphabet remains more popular for writing of Adamawa Fulfulde than Latin.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The Adamawa Fulfulde Ajami alphabet is the result of many decades of efforts to standardize, starting from the 1960s.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] By the 1990s, the orthography was well established.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In 1998, at the JCMWA/MICCAO conference in Ngaoundéré, Cameroon, over 100 representatives from 14 West African countries agreed that this orthography would be a good standard for writing the Fulfulde language with Arabic script.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The alphabet consists of 33 basic letters, 28 plus *hamaza* from Arabic, and 4 are new letters created for use in Fulfulde.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] 10 of the Arabic letters are only used for writing Arabic loanwords, and have no use for writing indigenous Fulfulde words.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter does come in the beginning of words as a vowel diacritic carrier for common Arabic loanwords.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Character unique to Fulfulde, not found in Arabic.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [θ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter is pronounced as [h] in Fulfulde, and is used for representing the sound [h] (except in Arabic loanwords).
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The latter is only used in Arabic loanwords in Fulfulde.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [x] in Arabic, but as [h] or [x] in Fulfulde.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter has a variation of pronunciations in different local dialects.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [sˤ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [dˤ] in Arabic, but as [d] in Fulfulde.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This is the local indigenous innovation in the Adamawa dialectical area.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [q] in Arabic, but as [k~g] in Fulfulde.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] , in which case it will not carry any diacritic.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [w], or it lengthens vowels [o] or [u].
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [j], or it lengthens vowel [i].
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Letter used for lengthening of vowel [e].
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde, there are 4 prenasalized consonants.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Prenasalized consonants are written as a digraph (combination of two consonants).
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The first letter of the digraph representing a prenasalized consonant cannot take any diacritic, including zero-vowel diacritic *sukun* '◌ْ‎'.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Like other languages that have historically been written within what's known as the Ajami tradition, there is a full relaince on diacritics for writing vowels.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Arabic there are only three diacritics, which represent [a] '◌َ‎', [u] [i] '◌ُ‎', and [i] '◌ِ‎'.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The general tradition is that when there are vowels that don't exist in Arabic, new diacritics are created.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde these include the Quranic imāla '◌ٜ‎' for vowel [e], and a special diacritic '◌ٛ‎' for vowel [o].
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Unlike Arabic orthography, or other Arabic-derived scripts, in Ajami tradition, all diacritics are written.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Even letters that don't have any vowels, are written with a *zero-vowel/sukun* '◌ْ‎' diacritic.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Vowels are lengthened by combining the diacritic with a follow-up letter, just as is the tradition in Arabic.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] These follow-up letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] ‎' can be part of a digraph representing prenasalized consonants.
[src:chechen-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In these instances, these two letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:chechen-language/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:chechen-language/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Before the Russian conquest, most writings in Chechnya consisted of Islamic texts and clan histories, written usually in Arabic but sometimes also in Chechen using Arabic script.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The Chechen literary language was created after the October Revolution, and the Latin script began to be used instead of Arabic for Chechen writing in the mid-1920s.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The Cyrillic script was adopted in 1938.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Almost the entire library of Chechen medieval writing in Arabic and Georgian script about the land of Chechnya and its people was destroyed by Soviet authorities in 1944, leaving the modern Chechens and modern historians with a destroyed and no longer existent historical treasury of writings.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The Chechen diaspora in Jordan, Turkey, and Syria is fluent but generally not literate in Chechen except for individuals who have made efforts to learn the writing system.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The Cyrillic alphabet is not generally known in these countries, and thus for Jordan and Syria, they mostly use the Arabic alphabet, while in Turkey they use the Latin alphabet.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Chechen is the most-spoken Northeast Caucasian language.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Together with the closely related Ingush, with which there exists a large degree of mutual intelligibility and shared vocabulary, it forms the Vainakh branch.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] There are a number of Chechen dialects: Aukh, Chebarloish, Malkhish, Nokhchmakhkakhoish, Orstkhoish, Sharoish, Shuotoish, Terloish, Itum-Qalish and Himoish.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Dialects of Chechen can be classified by their geographic position within the Chechen Republic.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The dialects of the northern lowlands are often referred to as "*Oharoy muott*" (literally "lowlander's language") and the dialect of the southern mountain tribes is known as "*Laamaroy muott*" (lit.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] *Oharoy muott* forms the basis for much of the standard and literary Chechen language, which can largely be traced to the regional dialects of Urus-Martan and contemporary Grozny.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Laamaroy dialects include Chebarloish, Sharoish, Itum-Qalish, Kisti, and Himoish.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Until recently, however, Himoy was undocumented and was considered a branch of Sharoish, as many dialects are also used as the basis of intertribal (teip) communication within a larger Chechen "*tukkhum*".
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Laamaroy dialects such as Sharoish, Himoish and Chebarloish are more conservative and retain many features from Proto-Chechen.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] For instance, many of these dialects lack a number of vowels found in the standard language which were a result of long-distance assimilation between vowel sounds.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Additionally, the Himoy dialect preserves word-final, post-tonic vowels as a schwa [ə].
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Literary Chechen is based on Plains Chechen, spoken around Grozny and Urus-Martan.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] According to the Russian Census of 2020, 1,490,000 people reported being able to speak Chechen in Russia.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Chechen is an official language of Chechnya.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Chechens in Jordan have good relations with the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan and are able to practice their own culture and language.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Chechen language usage is strong among the Chechen community in Jordan.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Jordanian Chechens are bilingual in both Chechen and Arabic, but do not speak Arabic among themselves, only speaking Chechen to other Chechens.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Some Jordanians are literate in Chechen as well, having managed to read and write to people visiting Jordan from Chechnya.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Some phonological characteristics of Chechen include its wealth of consonants and sounds similar to Arabic and the Salishan languages of North America, as well as a large vowel system resembling those of Swedish and German.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The Chechen language has, like most languages of the Caucasus, a large number of consonants: about 40 to 60 (depending on the dialect and the analysis), far more than most European languages.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Typical of the region, a four-way distinction between voiced, voiceless, ejective and geminate fortis stops is found.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Furthermore, all variants except the ejective are subject to phonemic pharyngealization.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Nearly any consonant may be fortis because of focus gemination, but only the ones above are found in roots.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The consonants of the *t* cell and /l/ are denti-alveolar; the others of that column are alveolar. /x/ is a back velar, but not quite uvular.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The lateral /l/ may be velarized, unless it is followed by a front vowel.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The trill /r/ is usually articulated with a single contact, and therefore sometimes described as a tap [ɾ].
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Except in the literary register, and even then only for some speakers, the voiced affricates /dz/, /dʒ/ have merged into the fricatives /z/, /ʒ/.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] A voiceless labial fricative /f/ is found only in European loanwords. /w/ appears both in diphthongs and as a consonant; as a consonant, it has an allophone [v] before front vowels.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Approximately twenty pharyngealized consonants (marked with superscript ˤ) also appear in the table above.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Labial, alveolar and postalveolar consonants may be pharyngealized, except for ejectives.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Except when following a consonant, /ʢ/ is phonetically [ʔˤ], and can be argued to be a glottal stop before a "pharyngealized" (actually epiglottalized) vowel.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] However, it does not have the distribution constraints characteristic of the anterior pharyngealized (epiglottalized) consonants.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Although these may be analyzed as an anterior consonant plus /ʢ/ (they surface for example as [dʢ] when voiced and [pʰʜ] when voiceless), Nichols argues that given the severe constraints against consonant clusters in Chechen, it is more useful to analyze them as single consonants.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Unlike most other languages of the Caucasus, Chechen has an extensive inventory of vowel sounds, putting its range higher than most languages of Europe (most vowels being the product of environmentally conditioned allophonic variation, which varies by both dialect and method of analysis).
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Many of the vowels are due to umlaut, which is highly productive in the standard dialect.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] None of the spelling systems used so far have distinguished the vowels with complete accuracy.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Nasalization is imposed by the genitive, infinitive, and for some speakers the nominative case of adjectives.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Nasalization is not strong, but it is audible even in final vowels, which are devoiced.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] In closed syllables, long vowels become short in most dialects (not Kisti), but are often still distinct from short vowels (shortened [i], [u], [ɔ] and [ɑ̈] vs. short [ɪ], [ʊ], [o], and [ə], for example), although which ones remain distinct depends on the dialect.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] /æ/, /æː/ and /e/, /eː/ are in complementary distribution (/æ/ occurs after pharyngealized consonants, whereas /e/ does not and /æː/—identical with /æ/ for most speakers—occurs in closed syllables, while /eː/ does not) but speakers strongly feel that they are distinct sounds.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Pharyngealization appears to be a feature of the consonants, though some analyses treat it as a feature of the vowels.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] However, Nichols argues that this does not capture the situation in Chechen well, whereas it is more clearly a feature of the vowel in Ingush: Chechen [tsʜaʔ] "one", Ingush [tsaʔˤ], which she analyzes as /tsˤaʔ/ and /tsaˤʔ/.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Vowels have a delayed murmured onset after pharyngealized voiced consonants and a noisy aspirated onset after pharyngealized voiceless consonants.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The high vowels /i/, /y/, /u/ are diphthongized, [əi], [əy], [əu], whereas the diphthongs /je/, /wo/ undergo metathesis, [ej], [ow].
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Chechen permits syllable-initial clusters /st px tx/ and non-initially also allows /x r l/ plus any consonant, and any obstruent plus a uvular of the same manner of articulation.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The only cluster of three consonants permitted is /rst/.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Numerous inscriptions in the Georgian script are found in mountainous Chechnya, but they are not necessarily in Chechen.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Later, the Arabic script was introduced for Chechen, along with Islam.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The Chechen Arabic alphabet was first reformed during the reign of Imam Shamil, and then again in 1910, 1920 and 1922.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] At the same time, the alphabet devised by Peter von Uslar, consisting of Cyrillic, Latin, and Georgian letters, was used for academic purposes.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] In 1911 it too was reformed but never gained popularity among the Chechens themselves.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The current official script for Chechen language is Cyrillic.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] This script was created and adopted in 1938, replacing the Latin script prior to it.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Up until 1992, only the Cyrillic script was used for Chechen.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] After the collapse of the Soviet Union and the de facto secession of the Chechen Republic of Ichkeria from Russia, a new Latin script was devised and was used parallel to Cyrillic until the dissolution of the separatist state.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] A new set of orthography rules for the Chechen language was prepared in 2020.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] In particular, it replaces the letters «я», «яь», «ю», and «юь» with «йа», «йаь», «йу», and «йуь», except for loanwords and proper names.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Thus, the letters Юь юь and Яь яь have been excluded from the Chechen alphabet.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The updated rules of Chechen orthography came into force on January 1, 2022.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Lower-case palochka, ⟨ӏ⟩, is found in handwriting.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Usually, palochka uppercase and lowercase forms consistent in print or upright, but only upper-case ⟨Ӏ⟩ is normally used in computers.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The first time that the Latin alphabet was introduced, was in 1925, replacing Arabic alphabet.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Further minor modifications in 1934, unified Chechen orthography with Ingush.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] But the Latin alphabet was abolished in 1938, being replaced with Cyrillic.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] In 1992, with the de facto secession of Chechen Republic of Ichkeria from Russia, a new Latin Chechen alphabet was introduced and used in parallel with the Cyrillic alphabet.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] This was the second time a Latin-based orthography was created for Chechen.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] But after the defeat of the Chechen Republic of Ichkeria government by the Russian Armed Forces, the Cyrillic alphabet was restored.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The first, most widespread modern orthography for Chechen was the Arabic script, adopted in the 19th century.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Chechen was not a traditionally written language, but due to the public's familiarity with the Arabic script – as the script of instruction in the region's Islamic and Quranic schools – the Arabic alphabet was first standardized and adopted for Chechen during the reign of Imam Shamil.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Islam has been the dominant religion in Chechnya since the 16th century, and there were 200 religious schools as well as more than 3000 pupils in Chechnya and Ingushetia.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Thus the Arabic script was well established among the speakers of Chechen.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] However, the Arabic alphabet would not be suitable for Chechen, and so modifications would be needed.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The Arabic alphabet underwent various iterations, improvements and modifications for the Chechen language.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Within Chechen society, these modifications were not without controversy.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The Muslim clergy and the more conservative segments of Chechen society initially resisted any changes to the Arabic script, with the belief that this script was sacred due to its association with Islam, and was not to be changed.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The clergy and Islamic educational institutions opposed each and every iteration of proposed reforms in the Arabic script.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The letter ڮ ‎ equivalent to Cyrillic letter "Кӏ" and representing the sound /kʼ/.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] In 1910, Sugaip Gaisunov proposed additional reforms that brought Arabic alphabet closer to Chechen's phonetic requirements.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] In Sugaip Gaisunov's reforms, the letters ص ‎ (*ṣād/sād*) and ض ‎ (*zād/ḍād*) had their usage limited to Arabic loanwords but were not eliminated due to opposition from clergy and conservative segments of Chechen society.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The overbar signified a vowel use when needed to avoid confusions.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] This modification did not persist in the Chechen alphabet.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Thus, the 1910 iteration of the Arabic script continued being used until 1920.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Eldarkhanov were a great final step in creating a modified Arabic script that represents Chechen consonants.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] However, the Arabic alphabet still was not suitable in representing Chechen vowel sounds.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Arabic script itself uses harakat, meaning that most but not all vowels are shown with diacritics, which are in most cases left unwritten.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The process of transforming Arabic script into a full alphabet for use by a non-Arabic language has been a common occurrence, and has been done in Uyghur, Kazakh, Kurdish and several more Arabic-derived scripts.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Thus a final revision on Chechen Arabic script occurred, in which vowel sounds were standardized.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] Table below lists the 41 letters of the final iteration of Chechen Arabic Alphabet, as published by Chechen Authorities at the time, prior to 1925, their IPA values, and their Cyrillic equivalents.
[src:chechen-language/chechen-language] The single letters and digraphs that count as separate letters of the alphabet, along with their correspondences, are as follows.
